00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:02.410
siRNA was able to effectively down-regulate not only wild type,

239
00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:05.580
but also mutant HIF2 alpha in cells in culture.

240
00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:09.350
So we tested this siRNA in

241
00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:13.900
mice implanted with tumor grafts that were dependent on HIF 2 and that expressed

242
00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:17.580
the integrins on the cell surface. Just going to show you here one example.

243
00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:21.260
This was a very aggressive tumor. As you can see over the course of three weeks,

244
00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:23.420
the tumor was growing very significantly.

245
00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:25.560
This is an orthotopic implantation.

246
00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:29.239
And then with the siRNA, the growth was

247
00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:33.140
significantly attenuated. You can see this here

248
00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:37.340
assessed by MRI, and then here looking at actual

249
00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:38.060
tumor volume.

250
00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:42.980
By immunohistochemistry, we could see that there was profound suppression of HIF

251
00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.900
2 alpha protein, and this is quantitated here in this western blot, which

252
00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:50.700
is intentionally overexposed so that you can see that there

253
00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:53.580
is some residual but not very much HIF 2 alpha.

254
00:14:54.040 --> 00:14:57.380
There was profound suppression of human VEGF in the mouse, and of course, the only

255
00:14:57.420 --> 00:15:00.640
source of human VEGF is the tumor. So we did these

256
00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:04.410
experiments in about half a dozen tumor grafts, and this provided a proof of

257
00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:08.440
principle for this siRNA therapy and set the foundation for this phase

258
00:15:08.500 --> 00:15:09.480
one clinical trial

259
00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:12.320
which in my view provides a proof of concept.

260
00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:17.260
This, as the other phase one clinical trial, in most phase one clinical trials,

261
00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:21.320
this was a dose escalation trial with a three plus three design, three

262
00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:25.100
different cohorts. And as you can see in this waterfall

263
00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:28.060
plot, there were only two partial responses.

264
00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:31.880
But we are looking for tumors that are both HIF 2-dependent and then that express

265
00:15:31.900 --> 00:15:35.500
the integrins, and this was an unselected patient population.

266
00:15:36.540 --> 00:15:40.060
I'm going to show you a case study. This was a patient of mine

267
00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:44.220
with paraneoplastic polycythemia, so someone that we thought would have

268
00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:45.620
HIF 2-dependent biology.

269
00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:50.480
The patient got only two doses of the siRNA because

270
00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.620
she had an acute coronary syndrome afterwards and came off a

271
00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:55.099
study.

272
00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.880
During the two-week washout period, and I could ask Eric and Brian

273
00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:02.200
whether they've seen something like this, they probably haven't.

274
00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:06.260
Tremendous progression within two weeks, somebody that had very aggressive

275
00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:10.020
disease. And then when treated with siRNA, you can see here

276
00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:13.840
after two doses that there was a persistent

277
00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:17.560
decrease in this target lesion. And as you can see

278
00:16:17.920 --> 00:16:21.880
here quantitated, and then suppression of the erythropoietin,

279
00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:25.740
which lasted for months. On biopsy, we could see that there was a HIF 2

280
00:16:25.780 --> 00:16:29.640
depletion, and we took a sample from the patient, and we implanted

281
00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:33.400
into a mouse, and we did the same trial in the mouse, and we could

282
00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:37.179
also see suppression of tumor growth and decrease HIF 2 alpha expression.

283
00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:41.099
So to me, this provides a proof of principle for successful

284
00:16:41.109 --> 00:16:43.500
siRNA targeting of HIF 2 alpha in patients.

285
00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:48.640
We've taken a second approach. So there was some toxicity from the

286
00:16:48.740 --> 00:16:49.440
siRNA.

287
00:16:50.680 --> 00:16:54.660
And we've been working with somebody at UT Southwestern, and this is

288
00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:56.160
using lipid nanoparticles, and

289
00:16:57.160 --> 00:16:59.920
I don't have much time to go over that, but this is published.

290
00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:04.401
In the last few minutes, I'm going to tell you about a recent story which

291
00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:08.181
implicates HIF 2 in the regulation of

292
00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:12.440
PTHrP, which is a critical mediator of

293
00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:16.440
paraneoplastic hypercalcemia. I'm going to show you that HIF 2

294
00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:18.450
induces the expression of PTHrP

295
00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:23.181
and is responsible for paraneoplastic

296
00:17:23.220 --> 00:17:24.940
hypercalcemia in a subset of patients.

297
00:17:26.901 --> 00:17:30.440
And of course, this is not only a poor prognostic factor, but something that

298
00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:33.620
untreated can cause significant problems in patients.

299
00:17:34.460 --> 00:17:37.000
So we're going to use this tumor graft platform.

300
00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:40.820
As I mentioned, we have a lot of patient samples, so despite the fact

301
00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:44.760
hypercalcemia occurs in up to 10% of the patients or so, we were able

302
00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:47.880
to identify about a dozen or so tumors that cause

303
00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:51.380
hypercalcemia, and then we're going to be treating them with this HIF 2 inhibitor,

304
00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:52.520
and then we're going to monitor them.

305
00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:57.460
So here you can see the cohort. I think this is nine

306
00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:00.820
tumor grafts, and in green are the ones where you can see that there was

307
00:18:00.860 --> 00:18:02.940
substantial downregulation of the calcium.

308
00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:05.220
This is quantitated here, so this was

309
00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.700
highly statistically significant.

310
00:18:08.780 --> 00:18:12.700
And you can also look at the PTHrP protein, which tends to

311
00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:14.960
correlate with a reduction in calcium levels.

312
00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:17.620
And again, this is also downregulated for the cohort.

313
00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:21.860
There were three tumor graft bearing mice where

314
00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:26.040
we saw less of an impact, in some cases, no impact at all

315
00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:27.240
on the calcium levels or

316
00:18:27.340 --> 00:18:31.108
PTHrP.We found

317
00:18:31.148 --> 00:18:34.708
that this improvement in hypercalcemia was associated with better

318
00:18:34.748 --> 00:18:35.908
mobility scores

319
00:18:36.808 --> 00:18:40.268
in the mice gain weight, and as expected, there was

320
00:18:40.428 --> 00:18:44.008
reduced dystrophic calcification and renal

321
00:18:44.108 --> 00:18:47.868
injury. So these are all improvements associated with the

322
00:18:47.888 --> 00:18:48.928
lower calcium levels.

323
00:18:49.968 --> 00:18:53.848
Interestingly, in these mice where we saw

324
00:18:53.908 --> 00:18:57.708
control of the calcium, in the majority of them, we saw a reduction in

325
00:18:57.768 --> 00:18:58.528
tumor volume.

326
00:19:00.068 --> 00:19:03.768
And indeed, if we take all of the mice that we have been treated

327
00:19:03.868 --> 00:19:07.168
with HIF-2 inhibitors, and we compare the normal calcemic with the

328
00:19:07.208 --> 00:19:10.497
hypercalcemic mice, and here you're looking at the reduction

329
00:19:11.288 --> 00:19:14.218
in tumor volume, the percentage responsiveness rather.

330
00:19:14.248 --> 00:19:18.188
You can see that in normal calcemia maybe the percentage is about 50%

331
00:19:18.228 --> 00:19:22.068
or so where we see some level of responsiveness, but this is significantly

332
00:19:22.128 --> 00:19:25.908
higher in the hypercalcemia, suggesting the hypercalcemia could be a predicted

333
00:19:25.948 --> 00:19:26.508
biomarker.

334
00:19:29.168 --> 00:19:32.278
Now, one of the things that happens when you treat with effective drugs is that

335
00:19:32.308 --> 00:19:34.787
you're going to have control of paraneoplastic syndromes.

336
00:19:34.848 --> 00:19:37.988
So we asked the question, how quickly could we see an effect?

337
00:19:38.308 --> 00:19:42.188
And at four days, we don't see any change in the number of tumor cells as assessed

338
00:19:42.228 --> 00:19:46.148
by tumor volume, but we could already see very profound down-regulation

339
00:19:46.188 --> 00:19:49.868
of PTHrP. In keeping with the notion that this was

340
00:19:49.968 --> 00:19:53.488
not an indirect effect from tumor regression, but rather a

341
00:19:53.588 --> 00:19:54.488
direct effect.

342
00:19:55.348 --> 00:19:59.168
And you can see that even within four days, we can see down-regulation of

343
00:19:59.208 --> 00:19:59.888
calcium levels.

344
00:20:01.908 --> 00:20:05.748
I mentioned before that HIF-2 alpha may be a biomarker, and when we perform

345
00:20:05.768 --> 00:20:08.968
immunohistochemistry, we found that HIF-2 alpha levels were

346
00:20:09.388 --> 00:20:13.308
substantially higher in tumors that tend to be hypercalcemic compared to

347
00:20:13.328 --> 00:20:17.028
tumors that are normal calcemic. And this is evaluating both a tumor graph

348
00:20:17.088 --> 00:20:19.388
microarray as well as individual slides.

349
00:20:21.448 --> 00:20:25.408
So we wanted to understand what these tumors look like in patients,

350
00:20:25.608 --> 00:20:27.208
and we focused on patients that had

351
00:20:28.348 --> 00:20:31.548
primary tumors in place, had an elevated calcium that then

352
00:20:31.568 --> 00:20:35.428
normalized after a nephrectomy, and we identified 26 such

353
00:20:35.448 --> 00:20:39.357
patients. These are patients that did not have elevated PTH or

354
00:20:39.447 --> 00:20:41.648
bone metastasis, which could be confounding factors.

355
00:20:42.308 --> 00:20:45.968
And what we found, as in the tumor graphs, that the vast majority were

356
00:20:46.228 --> 00:20:47.668
of clear cell histology.

357
00:20:48.668 --> 00:20:52.588
They were also, interestingly, of high grade, so the vast majority were

358
00:20:52.608 --> 00:20:56.088
Grade 3 or Grade 4, and 50% of them were either

359
00:20:56.168 --> 00:20:58.308
sarcomatoid, rhabdoid, or both.

360
00:20:59.348 --> 00:21:03.068
So these are features typical of very aggressive

361
00:21:03.128 --> 00:21:06.808
kidney cancer. Interestingly, even in the sarcomatoid tumors

362
00:21:07.128 --> 00:21:10.128
that were hypercalcemic, we could see high levels of HIF-2 alpha.

363
00:21:12.468 --> 00:21:16.378
Now, one question that people ask sometimes is how is it that not all of

364
00:21:16.408 --> 00:21:19.168
the tumors that are HIF-2 dependent have hypercalcemia?

365
00:21:19.177 --> 00:21:22.728
And indeed, we know that VHL patients will rarely have hypercalcemia, and most of

366
00:21:22.768 --> 00:21:25.808
them are responsive when you treat them with a HIF-2 inhibitor.

367
00:21:26.468 --> 00:21:27.338
And what we found,

368
00:21:28.168 --> 00:21:32.108
but before I go there, I'm going to show you that HIF-2 directly binds to the

369
00:21:32.128 --> 00:21:35.148
promoter sequences, induces the expression of our reporter.

370
00:21:35.188 --> 00:21:37.208
You can see this data here. So if we treat with a HIF-2

371
00:21:38.308 --> 00:21:41.568
inhibitor, a luciferase expressed downstream of the

372
00:21:41.638 --> 00:21:44.748
PTHrP promoter sequences, you can see down-regulation,

373
00:21:45.768 --> 00:21:48.308
and in cheap assays we can see decreased binding to HIF-2.

374
00:21:48.968 --> 00:21:52.728
Now on to what I was saying. So when we did whole genome ATAC

375
00:21:52.808 --> 00:21:56.788
sequencing, and we found that in the hypercalcemic lines, not just the

376
00:21:56.828 --> 00:22:00.648
promoter, but the whole PTHLH gene, which encodes

377
00:22:00.688 --> 00:22:04.548
PTHrP, had open chromatin. And if we look at tumors

378
00:22:04.568 --> 00:22:08.128
that are not hypercalcemic, and most of them are responsive to the HIF-2

379
00:22:08.148 --> 00:22:10.928
inhibitor, you can see that this locus is not open.

380
00:22:11.468 --> 00:22:15.108
Now, if we look at other canonical targets of HIF-2, you can see that

381
00:22:15.388 --> 00:22:19.188
they are open in both the hypercalcemic as well as the

382
00:22:19.228 --> 00:22:23.148
normal calcemic tumor, suggesting that one reason why some tumors

383
00:22:23.188 --> 00:22:26.868
may have paraneoplastic hypercalcemia is because the PTHLH locus is

384
00:22:26.928 --> 00:22:29.008
accessible for HIF-2 dependent transcription.

385
00:22:29.788 --> 00:22:33.608
We also asked what happens to the locus when you treat with a HIF-2

386
00:22:33.628 --> 00:22:37.528
inhibitor. And what we found is that when, and

387
00:22:37.608 --> 00:22:41.178
here in red are the HIF-2 inhibitor treated tumor graphs,

388
00:22:41.968 --> 00:22:45.728
you can see that there is not much difference either in the promoter

389
00:22:46.168 --> 00:22:47.427
or in the coding sequences

390
00:22:48.588 --> 00:22:50.288
when you treat with a HIF-2 inhibitor.

391
00:22:50.408 --> 00:22:53.888
In contrast, we had two lines that had paraneoplastic

392
00:22:53.898 --> 00:22:57.668
polycythemia, and when we look at the EPO gene, you

393
00:22:57.708 --> 00:23:01.188
can see that there is decreased accessibility when you treat with a HIF-2

394
00:23:01.208 --> 00:23:05.148
inhibitor in keeping with the idea that HIF-2 in this context

395
00:23:05.188 --> 00:23:09.158
is functioning as a pioneering transcription factor, but not in the

396
00:23:09.188 --> 00:23:13.168
context of PTHLH. And I don't know that there are other examples of this, but

397
00:23:13.208 --> 00:23:16.968
this suggests that there is a context dependency to the idea of being a

398
00:23:17.008 --> 00:23:18.428
pioneer transcription factor.

399
00:23:19.808 --> 00:23:23.678
We had the opportunity to test this concept prospectively in a couple of patients.

400
00:23:23.708 --> 00:23:27.468
It's a patient of mine that had sarcomatoid clear cell renal cell carcinoma, that

401
00:23:27.508 --> 00:23:31.168
had hypercalcemia, that had progressed on prior therapy and was

402
00:23:31.228 --> 00:23:35.148
treated with bel sutifan. And as you can see here, in less than two weeks,

403
00:23:35.248 --> 00:23:38.888
we corrected hypercalcemia, and there was a profound down-regulation of PTHrP.

404
00:23:39.868 --> 00:23:43.288
And this is data from a patient that had been treated with zoledronate, but the

405
00:23:43.328 --> 00:23:46.888
point I'm making is that when the patient got bel sutifan, you can see that the

406
00:23:46.908 --> 00:23:50.447
PTHrP became normalized within two days.

407
00:23:52.028 --> 00:23:55.528
Although at two days, we are not seeing a significant drop in calcium levels, which

408
00:23:55.568 --> 00:23:58.168
is approaching normal levels.

409
00:23:59.608 --> 00:24:02.808
Just to point out that there was a second study from Bill Kaelin's group,

410
00:24:03.388 --> 00:24:06.328
looking at the same concept,

411
00:24:07.208 --> 00:24:10.868
but with an emphasis on PTHrP mediated effects on

412
00:24:10.928 --> 00:24:13.768
cachexia, which was presented here.All right.

413
00:24:14.008 --> 00:24:17.528
I'm a little bit over time, so I'm going to skip the

414
00:24:17.568 --> 00:24:21.368
conclusions. Suffice to say that this is an exciting academic story,

415
00:24:21.388 --> 00:24:24.188
going from the discovery of a gene to a first-in-class drug.

416
00:24:24.748 --> 00:24:26.828
And I will just finish by acknowledging the people.

417
00:24:26.948 --> 00:24:29.208
So these are the people in my group.

418
00:24:29.268 --> 00:24:31.068
I originally led the hypercalcemia study.

419
00:24:31.428 --> 00:24:35.328
Alaina is our biostatistician, Vanina manages our tumor graph platform,

