00:24:35.368 --> 00:24:38.388
and Bing was the bioinformatician involved in the study as well.

421
00:24:39.108 --> 00:24:41.728
Kevin was the lead author of the Phase 1 clinical trial.

422
00:24:41.768 --> 00:24:44.068
We worked very closely with Payal and our radiologist.

423
00:24:44.608 --> 00:24:46.528
These are other UT Southwestern collaborators.

424
00:24:46.588 --> 00:24:50.288
Really emphasize Rick Brewik, Kevin Gardner, and Steve

425
00:24:50.328 --> 00:24:52.848
McKnight, who play critical roles in this.

426
00:24:53.568 --> 00:24:57.548
These are the clinical teams. So this is the PT-2385 Phase 1

427
00:24:57.588 --> 00:25:01.568
team with Brian, and this is the Aro-HIF2 team.

428
00:25:02.408 --> 00:25:03.468
So thank you for your attention.

429
00:25:06.828 --> 00:25:10.788
Thanks, Jim. That was a great journey through a few decades of HIF biology.

430
00:25:10.848 --> 00:25:12.478
Congrats to the UT Southwestern team.

431
00:25:12.528 --> 00:25:15.628
We maybe just have a minute for questions, and I just wanted to ask.

432
00:25:16.938 --> 00:25:20.128
So you presented the work on the HIF-2 binding pocket mutation.

433
00:25:20.228 --> 00:25:24.108
Is there other data out there on other mutations, or have other people found

434
00:25:24.148 --> 00:25:27.788
the same mutations? I'm not aware of other data on the

435
00:25:27.848 --> 00:25:28.908
mechanism of resistance.

436
00:25:29.048 --> 00:25:29.208
Right.

437
00:25:30.128 --> 00:25:33.628
To my knowledge, it remains the only data available.

438
00:25:34.668 --> 00:25:34.678
Okay.

439
00:25:34.688 --> 00:25:37.528
NeoMorphe was also referring to it in their presentations.

440
00:25:37.708 --> 00:25:37.888
Yeah.

441
00:25:38.388 --> 00:25:41.488
So you have the pocket mutation and then the mutation in HIF1-beta-

442
00:25:41.668 --> 00:25:41.678
Yeah

443
00:25:41.678 --> 00:25:44.108
... which is functioning as a second side suppression mutation.

444
00:25:44.388 --> 00:25:48.348
Yeah. I think given how much we're going to be using the drug clinically, that Eric

445
00:25:48.368 --> 00:25:51.348
and I will talk about, it's a pressing need for the field.

446
00:25:51.568 --> 00:25:51.927
Yeah.

447
00:25:52.388 --> 00:25:53.728
Eric, did you-- Oh, go ahead.

448
00:25:54.968 --> 00:25:55.048
Please.

449
00:25:55.088 --> 00:25:56.928
Hi, Eric Lightcap, Hyriscel.

450
00:25:58.368 --> 00:26:02.168
I was intrigued by your data around the EPO

451
00:26:02.748 --> 00:26:03.228
promoter.

452
00:26:04.708 --> 00:26:08.608
As you know, belzutifan over time has a fairly

453
00:26:08.648 --> 00:26:12.488
dramatic reduction in erythropoietin circulating levels, and then

454
00:26:12.528 --> 00:26:16.028
that recovers over time. Is there any evidence that this

455
00:26:16.228 --> 00:26:18.468
promoter effect is playing a role there?

456
00:26:19.548 --> 00:26:23.507
Great question. So I think that remains, as far as I know,

457
00:26:23.608 --> 00:26:24.388
enigmatic.

458
00:26:24.728 --> 00:26:24.868
All right.

459
00:26:25.428 --> 00:26:29.248
What triggers the re-expression of

460
00:26:29.368 --> 00:26:30.328
EPO over time?

461
00:26:31.288 --> 00:26:35.258
I understand from talking to the ARCOS folks

462
00:26:35.268 --> 00:26:38.128
that they believe that's not the case for castatifan-

463
00:26:38.138 --> 00:26:38.158
Mm-hmm

464
00:26:38.228 --> 00:26:41.708
... which I'm a little surprised about. I would like to see the data long term.

465
00:26:42.108 --> 00:26:45.208
But you're totally right. In the clinic, what we typically see is that there is

466
00:26:45.288 --> 00:26:48.248
profound suppression of EPO with anemia, but then over time, there is

467
00:26:48.848 --> 00:26:50.788
improvement, and the mechanism is not clear.

468
00:26:52.288 --> 00:26:54.478
We could try to model it in the mice.

469
00:26:54.508 --> 00:26:58.268
Obviously, trying to address that in patients may not be

