00:57:26.248 --> 00:57:28.748
indolent disease. That's probably what is reflecting there.

992
00:57:29.928 --> 00:57:32.928
So we presented the data. This is actually still not published yet, but we

993
00:57:32.988 --> 00:57:36.608
presented these data at ESMO, boy, I guess it was 2024 maybe,

994
00:57:36.948 --> 00:57:38.998
of the final analysis of Lightspark-005.

995
00:57:39.028 --> 00:57:41.688
Initial publication in New England Journal, and these were the follow-up data

996
00:57:41.728 --> 00:57:45.668
looking at overall survival. So as has been alluded

997
00:57:45.728 --> 00:57:49.568
to, this was a refractory kidney cancer population, one to

998
00:57:49.608 --> 00:57:52.628
three prior regimens. They had to have immune therapy, and they had to have at

999
00:57:52.668 --> 00:57:55.928
least one VEGF TKI, which again, are the standard therapies

1000
00:57:56.828 --> 00:58:00.428
for this disease. Seven hundred and fifty patients randomized equally to belzu,

1001
00:58:00.468 --> 00:58:04.428
120, which is the standard daily dose, or everolimus, which I would

1002
00:58:04.488 --> 00:58:06.368
call an old standard of care.

1003
00:58:07.448 --> 00:58:10.488
You could probably criticize the control arm of this trial, but nonetheless, it was

1004
00:58:10.548 --> 00:58:13.248
a standard of care at the time this trial was designed, which was a really long

1005
00:58:13.328 --> 00:58:16.228
time ago. PFS and OS is dual primaries.

1006
00:58:17.148 --> 00:58:20.668
So these are the updated PFS curves, and I would say a couple things that you see

1007
00:58:20.748 --> 00:58:24.528
here if my cursor works. So there's no difference in the median, right?

1008
00:58:24.568 --> 00:58:28.268
Five and a half months median. That's about what you get with TKIs in this setting,

1009
00:58:28.448 --> 00:58:31.108
six months, something like that for an average median PFS.

1010
00:58:31.148 --> 00:58:34.937
So about the same median. And you see these curves really

1011
00:58:35.228 --> 00:58:38.538
overlapping for the first six months, obviously accounting for that identical

1012
00:58:38.588 --> 00:58:42.428
median. But then you start to see a separation, and this is a theme we're going to

1013
00:58:42.507 --> 00:58:45.728
see with the other PFS curves that I'm going to show you in the adjuvant setting

1014
00:58:45.748 --> 00:58:49.008
and in combination in the refractory setting, that there seems to be a

1015
00:58:49.088 --> 00:58:52.308
tail-of-the-curve effect of belzu across multiple indications.

1016
00:58:52.808 --> 00:58:56.268
I didn't appreciate it as much when I first saw this data set, but with the newer

1017
00:58:56.348 --> 00:58:58.568
ones, I think we're appreciating it more.

1018
00:58:58.608 --> 00:59:02.558
And you can see nearly 20% of patients still progression free at two years.

1019
00:59:02.608 --> 00:59:05.528
That's a long time for refractory kidney cancer.

1020
00:59:05.588 --> 00:59:09.268
So there's clearly a subpopulation of patients, we don't yet know how to identify

1021
00:59:09.308 --> 00:59:11.728
them, that has a long and durable effect.

1022
00:59:11.848 --> 00:59:15.688
Not as long and durable as in the VHL syndrome patients, but these are

1023
00:59:15.728 --> 00:59:17.388
the best patients I have in my clinic.

1024
00:59:17.808 --> 00:59:21.228
They're on a monotherapy that's really well-tolerated with disease control now

1025
00:59:21.268 --> 00:59:24.788
measured in years. It doesn't get better than that in this refractory setting.

1026
00:59:26.728 --> 00:59:30.088
These are the OS curves. There was not an overall survival difference.

1027
00:59:30.128 --> 00:59:33.188
You see the curves, again, start to split a little later until you get to the

1028
00:59:33.228 --> 00:59:36.888
censoring. Hazard ratio below one, but a non-significant P value.

1029
00:59:37.468 --> 00:59:41.408
And belzu to date has not shown a survival advantage in any setting,

1030
00:59:42.268 --> 00:59:45.528
and not much has shown a survival advantage in the refractory setting in fairness.

1031
00:59:47.388 --> 00:59:50.228
These are the response data. So if you look on the left-hand side, there's that

1032
00:59:50.248 --> 00:59:54.128
response rate of 23%. So again, almost identical

1033
00:59:54.188 --> 00:59:56.208
to the phase two. That's actually decent.

1034
00:59:56.308 --> 00:59:58.668
Usually, you see the numbers go down in a phase three setting.

1035
00:59:59.208 --> 01:00:02.968
There was a small percentage of patients who had CRs, and this has been

1036
01:00:03.108 --> 01:00:03.928
seen, I would call it,

1037
01:00:05.368 --> 01:00:09.348
this is not a play on words, sporadically across these trials where we see maybe a

1038
01:00:09.388 --> 01:00:13.068
little bit of CR. So you can see it. I've seen it clinically, but it's not terribly

1039
01:00:13.108 --> 01:00:14.618
common. But as

1040
01:00:16.268 --> 01:00:19.228
we heard, the PD rate for monotherapy is quite high.

1041
01:00:19.658 --> 01:00:22.708
A third of patients will have primary progression, and that's a problem in

1042
01:00:22.788 --> 01:00:26.408
refractory kidney cancer when patients have often bulky and sometimes symptomatic

1043
01:00:26.468 --> 01:00:30.344
disease.And again, we don't yet know the

1044
01:00:30.404 --> 01:00:34.144
mechanism there. And one thing I tell patients from the start is, "Listen, this is

1045
01:00:34.224 --> 01:00:37.124
not a quick-acting drug." So I don't have

1046
01:00:37.964 --> 01:00:41.604
data about time to response, but it's often not at that first three-month scan.

1047
01:00:41.644 --> 01:00:43.284
It may be at a six or nine-month scan.

1048
01:00:43.324 --> 01:00:46.614
So for whatever reason, the kinetics of response are different with this

1049
01:00:46.624 --> 01:00:50.544
drug. On the right is the duration of response, and this is a reflection of what

1050
01:00:50.724 --> 01:00:52.364
I tried to point out in the PFS

1051
01:00:53.264 --> 01:00:57.144
graph, is that you see a longer duration, a longer tail of the curve with

1052
01:00:57.544 --> 01:01:00.074
belzutifan. Obviously, not many everolimus responders.

1053
01:01:00.164 --> 01:01:03.604
But patients who are in that 15, 20-ish percent who

1054
01:01:04.184 --> 01:01:06.164
do respond tend to do so quite durably.

1055
01:01:07.604 --> 01:01:11.464
This is a slide, I combined two slides together about time to first

1056
01:01:11.544 --> 01:01:14.834
onset, this middle part here, and then duration of some of the common side effects,

1057
01:01:14.844 --> 01:01:18.804
and Eric alluded to this. Anemia, an on-target side effect, super common.

1058
01:01:18.924 --> 01:01:21.944
I think almost everybody gets some degree of hemoglobin drop, and it obviously

1059
01:01:21.984 --> 01:01:25.524
depends on where they start. All the side effects pretty much occur early.

1060
01:01:26.064 --> 01:01:29.624
So it's the kind of drug maybe different than other things we do, where you sort of

1061
01:01:29.644 --> 01:01:31.704
know almost within the first weeks what you're in for.

1062
01:01:32.154 --> 01:01:35.004
The hypoxia is super early, I would say within days to weeks.

1063
01:01:35.104 --> 01:01:38.984
Anemia may be over many weeks to a couple of months, et cetera, as you see listed

1064
01:01:39.004 --> 01:01:40.804
here, but generally within a month or two.

1065
01:01:41.544 --> 01:01:44.624
We see this weight increase, which is a real thing, and I think is a reflection of

1066
01:01:44.644 --> 01:01:48.424
what Jim talked about in the HIF-2 cachexia link, et cetera, but it's a

1067
01:01:48.494 --> 01:01:51.704
real thing. And then on the far right is the average duration.

1068
01:01:51.744 --> 01:01:53.144
You can see there's huge ranges here.

1069
01:01:53.724 --> 01:01:56.404
Over many, many months, if not years.

1070
01:01:56.424 --> 01:02:00.244
But if you just look at the median. Duration of anemia is also a

1071
01:02:00.284 --> 01:02:03.324
function of how aggressive you are in managing it with erythroid-stimulating

1072
01:02:03.424 --> 01:02:05.884
agents. But you can see the other durations here.

1073
01:02:05.944 --> 01:02:09.504
So it's a very different side effect profile than our multi-targeted TKIs, which is

1074
01:02:09.544 --> 01:02:11.384
a good thing. Some unique side effects.

1075
01:02:11.484 --> 01:02:15.244
I think there's been a big learning curve from the VHL syndrome

1076
01:02:15.324 --> 01:02:17.244
days to the early belzu monotherapy.

1077
01:02:17.264 --> 01:02:20.384
I think it's now been around enough that I think comfort in managing these side

1078
01:02:20.404 --> 01:02:24.104
effects has increased tremendously, certainly in the academic setting, probably not

1079
01:02:24.144 --> 01:02:25.304
yet in the community setting.

1080
01:02:26.924 --> 01:02:30.784
So that was the data for approval. It's approved as

1081
01:02:30.804 --> 01:02:34.344
monotherapy in a refractory setting in the US. I commonly use it third line.

1082
01:02:34.404 --> 01:02:38.344
I give IO TKI frontline. I usually give TKI monotherapy second line, and then

1083
01:02:38.384 --> 01:02:40.464
belzu is probably my go-to third-line drug.

1084
01:02:40.504 --> 01:02:43.043
I'm sure we all use it differently in this setting.

1085
01:02:43.764 --> 01:02:46.973
So then there were two important data sets just presented at ASCO GU a couple of

1086
01:02:46.984 --> 01:02:49.604
months ago. The first was the 011 study.

1087
01:02:49.664 --> 01:02:53.504
This is now in a similar refractory setting as 005, but now it's in

1088
01:02:53.564 --> 01:02:56.764
combination with lenvatinib, a multi-targeted TKI,

1089
01:02:57.244 --> 01:02:59.104
compared to cabozantinib, which was,

