01:07:32.332 --> 01:07:36.232
low. I'm no statistician. When I look at these curves, I don't know where

1173
01:07:36.242 --> 01:07:39.792
the .78 comes from. Somebody needs to explain that to me, but the data's the data,

1174
01:07:39.832 --> 01:07:42.552
but really early time point for survival.

1175
01:07:42.632 --> 01:07:46.292
Hazard ratio below one, but, a huge confidence interval, non-significant at this

1176
01:07:46.392 --> 01:07:48.992
point. So we'll see. I think the feedback that

1177
01:07:49.932 --> 01:07:53.332
the way I feel and what I've sort of heard other experts say is that I think a lot

1178
01:07:53.352 --> 01:07:56.392
of people may wait for overall survival to give belzu in this setting.

1179
01:07:57.092 --> 01:08:00.272
I think it's different than immune therapy, and we can get into that debate.

1180
01:08:00.312 --> 01:08:03.912
But, nonetheless, a positive study that could change the standard of care or at

1181
01:08:03.952 --> 01:08:06.182
least provide another option in a subset of patients.

1182
01:08:06.952 --> 01:08:10.942
My biggest limitation in using this is the problem with

1183
01:08:10.952 --> 01:08:14.592
pembro monotherapy is half the patients won't recur anyway, right?

1184
01:08:14.612 --> 01:08:17.552
So even if you take high risk, half of those patients don't have cancer, they're

1185
01:08:17.572 --> 01:08:20.512
not going to recur, and you can only harm those patients with treatment.

1186
01:08:20.592 --> 01:08:23.302
Now you're doubling down on that, and you're giving them two drugs instead of one.

1187
01:08:24.282 --> 01:08:28.192
So it's kind of that balance of, am I willing to hurt this 50% more

1188
01:08:28.232 --> 01:08:32.192
to help an extra 6%, et cetera, and each doc and patient may make that decision

1189
01:08:32.213 --> 01:08:35.612
differently. This is the triplet study.

1190
01:08:35.663 --> 01:08:39.532
It's called 012. There was a press release two days ago I'll tell you about.

1191
01:08:39.972 --> 01:08:43.772
When I put these slides together, I didn't know the data was going to be out or the

1192
01:08:43.793 --> 01:08:47.652
press release, and so this was basically the final frontier of HIF inhibition.

1193
01:08:47.692 --> 01:08:50.652
This was an enormous frontline trial. This number's actually wrong.

1194
01:08:50.672 --> 01:08:54.572
It was over 1,800 patients. Len/pembro, ioTKI is

1195
01:08:54.583 --> 01:08:58.562
a standard of care in this setting, commonly used, and this was adding either

1196
01:08:58.592 --> 01:09:02.352
HIF inhibition to this investigative triplet or CTLA-4

1197
01:09:02.373 --> 01:09:06.352
inhibition to this. So basically testing almost every active mechanism in

1198
01:09:06.373 --> 01:09:09.753
kidney cancer and thinking, if one is good, two is better.

1199
01:09:09.812 --> 01:09:11.373
If two is better, three must be great, right?

1200
01:09:11.432 --> 01:09:13.432
That's how we do oncology drug development.

1201
01:09:14.552 --> 01:09:18.392
And I don't have a slide on this, but we just heard 48 hours ago that the study was

1202
01:09:18.432 --> 01:09:21.552
negative. Did not meet its primary endpoints for PFS or OS.

1203
01:09:22.032 --> 01:09:24.952
I have no idea why. There's going to be a huge autopsy, as you might imagine, and

1204
01:09:25.932 --> 01:09:29.632
HIF inhibition's already shown activity with lenva in that

1205
01:09:29.753 --> 01:09:33.112
011 study with pembro in 022 and basically every setting.

1206
01:09:33.213 --> 01:09:36.552
So it's really unclear to me biologically or otherwise what went on, but

1207
01:09:37.253 --> 01:09:39.432
we will find out. We'll certainly be talking about it a lot.

1208
01:09:40.392 --> 01:09:44.272
And this is a table that just puts all the data on one slide, and it goes from

1209
01:09:44.333 --> 01:09:47.452
left to right, from adjuvant frontline and then to the refractory settings.

1210
01:09:47.852 --> 01:09:50.753
You could see there's, again, different partners, et cetera, so it's a little bit

1211
01:09:50.833 --> 01:09:54.432
apples and oranges, but just to put all the numbers. This is that 012 frontline.

1212
01:09:54.472 --> 01:09:57.052
We don't have the data yet, but now know it's negative.

1213
01:09:57.062 --> 01:10:00.532
I hadn't put a table like this together before, but you see

1214
01:10:00.572 --> 01:10:03.622
relatively consistent effects. Again, different settings.

1215
01:10:03.732 --> 01:10:07.692
One's DFS, one's PFS, so I get that, but relatively consistent effect.

1216
01:10:07.732 --> 01:10:09.652
Again, notwithstanding the 012 results.

1217
01:10:10.372 --> 01:10:13.452
Non-significant overall survival, although two of these studies are pretty early.

1218
01:10:13.562 --> 01:10:16.352
We may or may not see that mature, et cetera.

1219
01:10:17.172 --> 01:10:20.932
And again, that primary PD rate, which as monotherapy is higher, but in

1220
01:10:20.972 --> 01:10:24.352
combo is much lower. So clearly an active approach across

1221
01:10:24.412 --> 01:10:26.212
multiple kidney cancer settings.

1222
01:10:27.292 --> 01:10:30.202
And then I just wanted to say one word about biomarkers before I finish up.

1223
01:10:30.232 --> 01:10:32.692
This is a poster that Merck presented again at ASCO GU.

1224
01:10:33.272 --> 01:10:35.712
We're just starting to get some biomarker data.

1225
01:10:37.272 --> 01:10:40.892
HIF inhibition, as you heard Jim and Eric talk about, it's ripe for

1226
01:10:40.912 --> 01:10:44.452
biomarker development. This is different than our very messy TKIs, which act on the

1227
01:10:44.472 --> 01:10:47.532
stroma. This is a tumor-targeted therapy and very focused.

1228
01:10:47.592 --> 01:10:51.172
So, Merck looked across-- this was a dose

1229
01:10:51.252 --> 01:10:53.072
escalation study, which I didn't talk about.

1230
01:10:53.112 --> 01:10:55.752
They tested, I think it was 120 daily and 200 daily.

1231
01:10:55.832 --> 01:10:59.112
Didn't turn out there was much difference, but they used this as an initial attempt

1232
01:10:59.152 --> 01:11:02.682
to look at biomarkers. And this table really just looks at

1233
01:11:03.452 --> 01:11:07.142
immunohistochemistry and gene expression scores across-- these are various Merck

1234
01:11:07.192 --> 01:11:10.812
proprietary collections of genes that they've used across their solid tumor

1235
01:11:10.912 --> 01:11:14.782
program. The bold is where there was significant associations with the various

1236
01:11:14.812 --> 01:11:18.452
clinical outcomes. So small study, hypothesis generating.

1237
01:11:18.492 --> 01:11:22.042
It is corrected for multiple testing, but still, I think a very initial sort of

1238
01:11:22.072 --> 01:11:25.792
foray, and these same markers will be looked at in 005 and other studies, I

1239
01:11:25.852 --> 01:11:29.312
imagine. So we're starting to get some hints of what might be important.

1240
01:11:30.452 --> 01:11:32.612
What's down here, they also looked at DNA alterations.

1241
01:11:32.632 --> 01:11:35.972
They looked at BAP1, which Jim has described very well, and it looked like BAP1

1242
01:11:36.012 --> 01:11:37.912
mutants had a better response to belzutifan.

1243
01:11:37.992 --> 01:11:40.072
Jim, I would love your thoughts about why that could be the case.

1244
01:11:40.172 --> 01:11:43.392
I would think it would be the opposite, so I don't know if this is a totally

1245
01:11:43.492 --> 01:11:47.032
spurious finding, but it's not an insignificant number of patients, right?

1246
01:11:47.072 --> 01:11:50.812
It's a decent number. So I just put it on there because it's something I don't

1247
01:11:50.852 --> 01:11:53.252
understand, and I think this field is just starting.

1248
01:11:55.592 --> 01:11:58.552
You heard Jim allude to, or maybe Eric as well, CASGADAtifan is made by a company

1249
01:11:58.592 --> 01:12:00.912
called Arcus. It's the other clinically advanced

1250
01:12:02.052 --> 01:12:04.832
HIF inhibitor in kidney cancer. It's not yet FDA approved.

1251
01:12:05.292 --> 01:12:07.952
I think they presented some data here as well,

1252
01:12:08.872 --> 01:12:10.232
and some of these slides came from them.

1253
01:12:11.112 --> 01:12:12.992
This was data presented at ASCO GU.

1254
01:12:13.032 --> 01:12:17.012
They have this study called ARC20, which has 10 different cohorts

1255
01:12:17.092 --> 01:12:20.672
now in various settings, in various combos, where they're just testing out what's

1256
01:12:20.692 --> 01:12:24.432
the activity. In the monotherapy cohort at what is now the

1257
01:12:24.452 --> 01:12:28.412
phase three dose of 100 daily, you see a response rate of 45%.

1258
01:12:28.552 --> 01:12:32.092
Small number of patients, but remember, that's about double what we saw with belzu

1259
01:12:32.112 --> 01:12:35.380
in a similar setting.All sorts of caveats to that statement.

1260
01:12:35.420 --> 01:12:39.280
We'll see how it holds up. There may or may not be some pharmacokinetic

1261
01:12:39.560 --> 01:12:40.860
advantages to this drug.

1262
01:12:41.700 --> 01:12:45.440
We also see a very low PD rate. Remember, it was 34% with Belzu,

1263
01:12:45.540 --> 01:12:47.000
although lower in the initial study.

1264
01:12:47.100 --> 01:12:51.020
So again, an interesting compound is always better to have more drugs in

1265
01:12:51.060 --> 01:12:55.000
a setting, at least from a clinical standpoint. Median PFS of 15 months.

1266
01:12:55.010 --> 01:12:58.460
So as these data have matured, they've become more and more impressive, and again,

1267
01:12:58.600 --> 01:13:01.040
some of the responses take a while to happen.

1268
01:13:01.080 --> 01:13:04.280
This is a study called Peak1, which is the registration study for

1269
01:13:04.320 --> 01:13:06.340
castadafam. This is

1270
01:13:07.820 --> 01:13:11.709
prior immune-exposed clear cell kidney cancer patients randomized to

1271
01:13:11.740 --> 01:13:15.500
either cabo alone, which as I told you is a standard of care, or castadafam plus

1272
01:13:15.540 --> 01:13:18.840
cabo. Looking at PFS, it's just open, starting to accrue.

1273
01:13:20.760 --> 01:13:24.540
And then my last couple slides are, I give this company a lot of credit for

1274
01:13:24.600 --> 01:13:27.900
doing some nice biomarker work with clinical development.

1275
01:13:28.040 --> 01:13:31.980
Usually it's all the clinical development and then we get to the biomarkers later.

1276
01:13:32.200 --> 01:13:35.349
They've done a nice job of incorporating biomarker development into their clinical

1277
01:13:35.420 --> 01:13:37.999
development. They've looked at serum IPAG in reduction.

1278
01:13:38.040 --> 01:13:40.620
That's what's on the left here, and this is a function of dose when they were still

1279
01:13:40.920 --> 01:13:44.640
playing around with dose. And then if you look at best

1280
01:13:44.700 --> 01:13:48.480
objective response by maximal serum IPAG and change, the

1281
01:13:48.500 --> 01:13:52.360
green is the responding patients, and you see them segregating a little more to the

1282
01:13:52.370 --> 01:13:56.120
right here. And so there is an association of deeper

1283
01:13:56.180 --> 01:13:59.460
IPAG reductions and a better chance of having an objective

1284
01:13:59.480 --> 01:14:03.390
response. All patients have some degree

1285
01:14:03.420 --> 01:14:06.700
of serum IPAG reduction, so it's deep versus less deep.

1286
01:14:06.720 --> 01:14:09.580
It's not that some patients don't have a reduction.

1287
01:14:09.680 --> 01:14:13.040
And this is just another way of basically saying the same thing, of looking at

1288
01:14:13.080 --> 01:14:17.060
serum IPAG and change now segregating it into the best objective response for these

1289
01:14:17.120 --> 01:14:20.980
recess categories, and you see these box and whisker plots go

1290
01:14:21.060 --> 01:14:24.300
down over time. And this on the right here is just the PFS data saying the same

1291
01:14:24.360 --> 01:14:27.240
thing. So this is obviously an on-treatment, right?

1292
01:14:27.300 --> 01:14:30.180
You don't know how deep somebody's going to suppress their IPAG before you start

1293
01:14:30.240 --> 01:14:34.080
treatment, so it's not a perfect predictive biomarker, but biologically, of course,

1294
01:14:34.540 --> 01:14:35.140
makes sense.

1295
01:14:36.540 --> 01:14:40.480
One thing they have looked at is tumor IPAG and mRNA expression, so this would be

1296
01:14:40.520 --> 01:14:44.500
a baseline biomarker if you had an available sample and looking at expression

1297
01:14:44.540 --> 01:14:47.640
as a function of what they call disease control, which people usually lump in

1298
01:14:47.680 --> 01:14:51.280
response and stable disease as disease control, which I don't love doing, but be

1299
01:14:51.320 --> 01:14:52.020
that as it may.

1300
01:14:52.840 --> 01:14:56.300
Again, I think these are early data, relatively small number of samples, but I

1301
01:14:56.320 --> 01:15:00.100
think biologically sensible, and I think we're going to have a

1302
01:15:00.140 --> 01:15:04.100
biomarker for HIF inhibition. We've spent 20 years trying to find one for

1303
01:15:04.140 --> 01:15:07.640
VEGF and 10 years for IO, and have failed miserably, but I think we will have one

1304
01:15:07.660 --> 01:15:08.540
for HIF inhibition.

1305
01:15:09.460 --> 01:15:09.560
We

1306
01:15:10.520 --> 01:15:13.420
have a trial called OPTIC, which is a biomarker-based study I won't talk about, but

1307
01:15:13.460 --> 01:15:16.220
we've looked at some HIF-2 gene expression.

1308
01:15:16.300 --> 01:15:18.000
There's different signatures out there, including

1309
01:15:19.460 --> 01:15:22.550
one that Jim's been involved with and other signatures that we've looked at.

1310
01:15:23.080 --> 01:15:26.520
In our hands, metastatic tumors exhibit increased HIF-2 signaling.

1311
01:15:26.580 --> 01:15:30.400
That's a good thing in the sense that if that's a marker for response, that

1312
01:15:30.440 --> 01:15:32.280
those are the patients we're treating in our clinic.

1313
01:15:34.760 --> 01:15:38.220
I don't have time to explain all our clusters, but cluster three and six comes from

1314
01:15:38.300 --> 01:15:42.000
a separate study, and it's these really biologically distinct tumors.

1315
01:15:42.040 --> 01:15:44.550
They're not angiogenic, they're not immune, they're something else.

1316
01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:48.110
And it was really interesting to us that they had the highest HIF signature scores.

1317
01:15:48.340 --> 01:15:51.760
I would have assumed that the angiogenic clusters would express HIF genes.

1318
01:15:52.320 --> 01:15:55.880
And I think why we're seeing additive effects clinically is because that's not the

1319
01:15:55.920 --> 01:15:59.369
case. So the biology of responding to angiogenic drugs and the biology of

1320
01:15:59.380 --> 01:16:00.980
responding to HIF drugs, I think is different.

1321
01:16:01.320 --> 01:16:04.520
Not entirely non-overlapping, but certainly not

1322
01:16:04.900 --> 01:16:07.760
entirely overlapping, and I think that's why we're seeing these broad clinical

1323
01:16:07.780 --> 01:16:08.240
effects.

1324
01:16:09.100 --> 01:16:12.480
We're about to embark on this study where we're going to do just a very small pilot

1325
01:16:12.560 --> 01:16:16.000
study looking at pre on treatment and progression biopsies,

1326
01:16:16.500 --> 01:16:18.480
and Jim, this is why I asked you the question about resistance.

1327
01:16:18.540 --> 01:16:22.410
So we hope to learn, looking at these gene expression changes

1328
01:16:22.460 --> 01:16:26.270
over time and really drill down on baseline predictors, looking at

1329
01:16:26.280 --> 01:16:28.360
mutations or other causes of resistance, et cetera.

1330
01:16:28.440 --> 01:16:30.060
This is still working its way through our system.

1331
01:16:30.080 --> 01:16:32.140
Hopefully by this summer we'll have this open.

1332
01:16:33.020 --> 01:16:36.880
So just to wrap up, HIF inhibition has clear activity across the spectrum of

1333
01:16:36.900 --> 01:16:40.460
kidney cancer. Why the frontline trial was negative, I have no idea, but we'll

1334
01:16:40.600 --> 01:16:42.660
figure that out in the next six months.

1335
01:16:43.420 --> 01:16:45.910
Exactly where to apply it, I think is something we're going to debate.

1336
01:16:46.560 --> 01:16:49.830
Is adjuvant the best? Is second line the best? Should it have a partner?

1337
01:16:49.900 --> 01:16:51.349
Do you want to save it for monotherapy?

1338
01:16:51.400 --> 01:16:54.700
I think we will be debating that for months, if not

1339
01:16:54.740 --> 01:16:58.200
years. And I'm really high on a lot of the early

1340
01:16:58.220 --> 01:17:02.210
biomarker work, right? Everybody stands up and talks about how we need

1341
01:17:02.220 --> 01:17:06.020
a biomarker. We've really not done great work in kidney cancer, not from

1342
01:17:06.030 --> 01:17:09.220
lack of trying, but lack of finding, but I think those are coming in kidney cancer.

1343
01:17:09.300 --> 01:17:12.840
So, thanks for your attention. I think we have a few minutes for any questions for

1344
01:17:12.880 --> 01:17:13.700
myself or the others.

1345
01:17:25.320 --> 01:17:26.920
Hi. Eric Lightcap again.

1346
01:17:28.480 --> 01:17:31.920
So I believe you had looked at KIM-1

1347
01:17:32.880 --> 01:17:35.500
as a biomarker for atezolizumab

1348
01:17:36.380 --> 01:17:38.810
and shown some association there.

1349
01:17:39.820 --> 01:17:43.120
Has there been much evaluation of

1350
01:17:43.340 --> 01:17:46.980
KIM-1 as a biomarker for HIF-2 alpha

1351
01:17:47.400 --> 01:17:47.460
inhibitors?

1352
01:17:47.500 --> 01:17:51.300
Yeah, it's a good question. I'm not aware of any data that's public

1353
01:17:51.360 --> 01:17:53.940
that's looked at that, but you can imagine it's on the list.

1354
01:17:54.240 --> 01:17:54.420
Yeah.

1355
01:17:54.780 --> 01:17:57.360
KIM-1, for those who don't know, kidney injury molecule 1.

1356
01:17:57.400 --> 01:18:01.380
There's some data in the adjuvant space in kidney cancer in a study

1357
01:18:01.420 --> 01:18:05.080
called IMmotion010 of atezolizumab, and now emerging some other advanced

1358
01:18:05.560 --> 01:18:08.020
spaces. It seems to be a marker of disease.

1359
01:18:08.360 --> 01:18:08.580
Right.

1360
01:18:08.920 --> 01:18:11.850
How much bulk of disease is there? It's more in metastatics, less in the adjuvant,

1361
01:18:11.900 --> 01:18:14.780
et cetera, and may be a marker of MRD in the adjuvant settings.

1362
01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:15.020
I

1363
01:18:15.980 --> 01:18:17.120
don't know if you are, Eric, or anybody.

1364
01:18:17.500 --> 01:18:21.420
I'm not aware of any data that's public around HIF inhibition,

1365
01:18:21.500 --> 01:18:23.740
but in the next year I'm sure there will be.

1366
01:18:23.760 --> 01:18:23.920
All right.

1367
01:18:24.640 --> 01:18:26.840
It's such an easy thing to measure. Everybody's looking at it.

1368
01:18:27.020 --> 01:18:27.030
Right.

1369
01:18:27.060 --> 01:18:27.280
Yeah.

1370
01:18:27.290 --> 01:18:28.100
All right.

1371
01:18:28.140 --> 01:18:30.500
Yeah. I think what's going to be interesting is that,

1372
01:18:31.940 --> 01:18:33.980
A, I think we know it's a marker of MRD.

1373
01:18:34.120 --> 01:18:37.620
B, I think the LightSpark 22 study is going to allow us to

1374
01:18:37.960 --> 01:18:41.700
understand better whether or not there's any association between the presence or

1375
01:18:41.780 --> 01:18:45.700
absence, and the probability of response to belzutifan, at least

1376
01:18:45.760 --> 01:18:49.408
in the adjuvant setting. So I think there's...

1377
01:18:49.428 --> 01:18:52.268
work that's being done, which is going to help us understand that, but there's

1378
01:18:52.308 --> 01:18:53.428
nothing currently available.

1379
01:18:54.128 --> 01:18:54.588
Any question?

1380
01:18:55.308 --> 01:18:58.898
Hi. Dan Crooks from the Neurologic Oncology Branch at

1381
01:18:58.948 --> 01:18:59.448
NCI.

1382
01:19:00.488 --> 01:19:04.348
And I suppose I could just go ask Ron this question, but

1383
01:19:04.408 --> 01:19:04.968
I'm curious.

1384
01:19:05.808 --> 01:19:08.628
We see the kidney tumors grow through belzutifan.

1385
01:19:09.868 --> 01:19:11.848
So question number one, do you think that there's

1386
01:19:12.648 --> 01:19:16.308
mechanisms other than genetic mechanisms that might be causing some of those tumors

1387
01:19:16.348 --> 01:19:18.248
to grow through belzutifan?

1388
01:19:19.048 --> 01:19:21.148
Question number two, I just don't know.

1389
01:19:21.488 --> 01:19:25.167
Do the other lesions ever grow through belzutifan, the DNA-

1390
01:19:25.208 --> 01:19:25.948
In VHL syndrome?

1391
01:19:26.208 --> 01:19:29.768
Yes, in VHL syndrome. Sorry. I'm purely speaking about that.

1392
01:19:29.808 --> 01:19:33.597
Yeah. So, your first question, I think the answer is we don't know,

1393
01:19:33.668 --> 01:19:36.788
but you could hypothesize that there might be some sort of microenvironmental

1394
01:19:36.848 --> 01:19:40.788
remodeling. We know that HIF-2 versus HIF-1 dependence

1395
01:19:40.828 --> 01:19:44.688
of immune subpopulations, they tend to be, I think, much more HIF-1

1396
01:19:44.748 --> 01:19:48.288
driven, but there's some variation as a function of which

1397
01:19:48.368 --> 01:19:51.868
subset we're talking about, and is that some way of actually engendering

1398
01:19:51.908 --> 01:19:52.488
resistance?

1399
01:19:53.608 --> 01:19:57.088
Good hypothesis. We don't have the clinical data yet to be able to answer

